# RAG Retrieval Quality Lab

Your support copilot is citing the wrong knowledge-base articles.

The product is a B2B SaaS support assistant. Customers ask product questions from inside tenant-scoped workspaces. The retrieval pipeline should search only documents that the current user can access, prefer fresh relevant material over stale keyword-heavy material, and return citations that actually support the answer.

Right now the retrieval path has production bugs:

- documents can leak across tenants
- admin-only documents can be returned to basic support users
- stale articles can outrank fresher relevant docs
- citations can reference chunks that were not returned

## What You Are Building

Repair the retrieval path so tenant-scoped product questions retrieve the right document chunks, respect ACL and freshness rules, produce grounded citations, and write an evaluation report.

## What Is Provided

- Docker Compose local simulator
- Qdrant vector search
- Postgres tenants, users, ACLs, document metadata, and eval results
- MinIO S3-compatible document storage
- deterministic fake embedding API
- public corpus, queries, and tests

## Main Files To Edit

- `src/retriever.py`
- `src/ranker.py`
- `src/citations.py`
- `src/eval_runner.py`

You may inspect supporting modules, but the durable fix should stay on the retrieval production path.

## Commands

```bash
make setup
make dev
make seed
make index
make test
make eval
make clean
```

`make dev` starts local services. `make seed` migrates Postgres, uploads documents to MinIO, and indexes chunks into Qdrant. `make test` runs the public tests. `make eval` writes `results/retrieval_report.json` and `results/summary.md`.

## Deliverables

- fixed retrieval implementation
- `results/retrieval_report.json`
- `results/summary.md`

## Evaluation

Public tests verify the visible contract. Additional evaluation checks may use harder fixtures to check tenant isolation, ACL handling, freshness, citation grounding, hardcoding resistance, and retrieval precision.

Do not add external credentials or live cloud services. The local simulator is the production environment for this exercise.
